# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: load-balancing-l4-l7
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] An **application delivery controller** (**ADC**) is a computer network device in a datacenter, often part of an application delivery network (ADN), that helps perform common tasks, such as those done by web accelerators to remove load from the web servers themselves.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] ADCs are often placed in the DMZ, between the outer firewall or router and a web farm.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] An Application Delivery Controller (ADC) is a type of server that provides a variety of services designed to optimize the distribution of load being handled by backend content servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] An ADC directs web request traffic to optimal data sources in order to remove unnecessary load from web servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] To accomplish this, an ADC includes many OSI layer 3-7 services, including load-balancing.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] ADCs are intended to be deployed within the DMZ of a computer server cluster hosting web applications and/or services.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] In this sense, an ADC can be envisioned as a drop-in load balancer replacement.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] Examine the Request URI and determine the type of resource being requested.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] Verify that the entity making the request is authorized to access the given URI.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] Perform any URI translation, if applicable.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] Lookup the pool of hosts associated with that resource type (e.g. image, stylesheet, HTML, etc).
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] In the case of login requests, the request may be translated, rather than simply forwarded, to an instance within a pool of authentication servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] In the case of static objects, the ADC may serve the object directly from its own internal cache or direct it to a dedicated static object repository.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] Maintain a table describing the health of the servers in every pool via one of several methods (e.g. average response time).
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] Forward the request to the server within the target pool with the best health score.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] In the context of Telco infrastructure, an ADC could provide access control services for a Gi-LAN area.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] Starting around 2004, first generation ADCs offered simple application acceleration and load balancing.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] By 2007, application acceleration products were available from many companies.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] Until leaving the market in 2012, Cisco Systems offered application delivery controllers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] Market leaders like F5 Networks, Radware, and Citrix had been gaining market share from Cisco in previous years.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] The ADC market segment became fragmented into two general areas: 1) general network optimization; and 2) application/framework specific optimization.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/application-delivery-controller] Both types of devices improve performance, but the latter is usually more aware of optimization strategies that work best with a particular application framework, focusing on ASP.NET or AJAX applications, for example.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] In computer science, **consistent hashing** is a special kind of hashing technique such that when a hash table is resized, only $n/m$ keys need to be remapped on average where n is the number of keys and m is the number of slots.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing evenly distributes cache keys across shards, even if some of the shards crash or become unavailable.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] In contrast, in most traditional hash tables, a change in the number of array slots causes nearly all keys to be remapped because the mapping between the keys and the slots is defined by a modular operation.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing is used by Content Delivery Networks because it is useful for distributing requests for content from a rotating population of web servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Tim Berners-Lee credits consistent hashing algorithms, and Daniel Lewin as their inventor, with solving the slashdotting problem which plagued the World Wide Web in the 1990s.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] The term "consistent hashing" was introduced by David Karger *et al.* at MIT for use in distributed caching, particularly for the web.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] This academic paper from 1997 in Symposium on Theory of Computing introduced the term "consistent hashing" as a way of distributing requests among a changing population of web servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Each slot is then represented by a server in a distributed system or cluster.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] The addition of a server and the removal of a server (during scalability or outage) requires only $num\_keys/num\_slots$ items to be re-shuffled when the number of slots (i.e. servers) change.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] The authors mention linear hashing and its ability to handle sequential server addition and removal, while consistent hashing allows servers to be added and removed in an arbitrary order.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] The paper was later re-purposed to address technical challenge of keeping track of a file in peer-to-peer networks such as a distributed hash table.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Teradata used this technique in their distributed database, released in 1986, although they did not use this term.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Teradata still uses the concept of a hash table to fulfill exactly this purpose.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Akamai Technologies was founded in 1998 by the scientists Daniel Lewin and F.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Thomson Leighton (co-authors of the article coining "consistent hashing").
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] In Akamai's content delivery network, consistent hashing is used to balance the load within a cluster of servers, while a stable marriage algorithm is used to balance load across clusters.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing has also been used to reduce the impact of partial system failures in large web applications to provide robust caching without incurring the system-wide fallout of a failure.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing is also the cornerstone of distributed hash tables (DHTs), which employ hash values to partition a keyspace across a distributed set of nodes, then construct an overlay network of connected nodes that provide efficient node retrieval by key.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Rendezvous hashing, designed in 1996, is a simpler and more general technique .
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] It achieves the goals of consistent hashing using the very different highest random weight (HRW) algorithm.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] However, when a server is added or removed during outage or scaling (when n changes), all the BLOBs in every server should be reassigned and moved due to rehashing, but this operation is expensive.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing was designed to avoid the problem of having to reassign every BLOB when a server is added or removed throughout the cluster.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] The central idea is to use a hash function that maps both the BLOB and servers to a unit circle, usually $2\pi$ radians.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] For example, $\zeta =\Phi \ \%\ 360$ (where $\Phi$ is hash of a BLOB or server's identifier, like IP address or UUID).
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Each BLOB is then assigned to the next server that appears on the circle in clockwise order.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] This provides an even distribution of BLOBs to servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] But, more importantly, if a server fails and is removed from the circle, only the BLOBs that were mapped to the failed server need to be reassigned to the next server in clockwise order.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Likewise, if a new server is added, it is added to the unit circle, and only the BLOBs mapped to that server need to be reassigned.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Importantly, when a server is added or removed, the vast majority of the BLOBs maintain their prior server assignments, and the addition of $n^{th}$ server only causes $1/n$ fraction of the BLOBs to relocate.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Although the process of moving BLOBs across cache servers in the cluster depends on the context, commonly, the newly added cache server identifies its "predecessor" and moves all the BLOBs, whose mapping belongs to this server (i.e. whose hash value is less than that of the new server), from it.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] However, in the case of web page caches, in most implementations there is no involvement of moving or copying, assuming the cached BLOB is small enough.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] When a request hits a newly added cache server, a cache miss happens and a request to the actual web server is made and the BLOB is cached locally for future requests.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] The redundant BLOBs on the previously used cache servers would be removed as per the cache eviction policies.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Let $h_{b}(x)$ and $h_{s}(x)$ be the hash functions used for the BLOB and server's unique identifier respectively.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] In practice, a binary search tree (BST) is used to dynamically maintain the ${\text{server ID}}$ within a cluster or hashring, and to find the successor or minimum within the BST, tree traversal is used.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] To avoid skewness of multiple nodes within the radian, which happen due to lack of uniform distribution of the servers within the cluster, multiple labels are used.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Those duplicate labels are called "virtual nodes" i.e. multiple labels which point to a single "real" label or server within the cluster.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] The amount of virtual nodes or duplicate labels used for a particular server within a cluster is called the "weight" of that particular server.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] A number of extensions to the basic technique are needed for effectively using consistent hashing for load balancing in practice.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] In the basic scheme above, if a server fails, all its BLOBs are reassigned to the next server in clockwise order, potentially doubling the load of that server.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] To ensure a more even redistribution of BLOBs on server failure, each server can be hashed to multiple locations on the unit circle.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] When a server fails, the BLOBs assigned to each of its replicas on the unit circle will get reassigned to a different server in clockwise order, thus redistributing the BLOBs more evenly.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Another extension concerns a situation where a single BLOB gets "hot" and is accessed a large number of times and will have to be hosted in multiple servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] In this situation, the BLOB may be assigned to multiple contiguous servers by traversing the unit circle in clockwise order.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] A more complex practical consideration arises when two BLOBs are hashed near each other in the unit circle and both get "hot" at the same time.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] In this case, both BLOBs will use the same set of contiguous servers in the unit circle.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] This situation can be ameliorated by each BLOB choosing a different hash function for mapping servers to the unit circle.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Rendezvous hashing, designed in 1996, is a simpler and more general technique, and permits fully distributed agreement on a set of k options out of a possible set of n options.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] It can in fact be shown that consistent hashing is a special case of rendezvous hashing.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] Because of its simplicity and generality, rendezvous hashing is now being used in place of Consistent Hashing in many applications.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] If key values will always increase monotonically, an alternative approach using a hash table with monotonic keys may be more suitable than consistent hashing.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/consistent-hashing] The $O(K/N)$ is an average cost for redistribution of keys and the $O(\log N)$ complexity for consistent hashing comes from the fact that a binary search among nodes angles is required to find the next node on the ring.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] In computing, **load balancing** is the process of distributing a set of tasks over a set of resources (computing units) with the aim of making their overall processing more efficient.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can optimize response time and avoid unevenly overloading some compute nodes while other compute nodes are left idle.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is the subject of research in the field of parallel computers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Two main approaches exist: static algorithms, which do not take into account the state of the different machines, and dynamic algorithms, which are usually more general and more efficient but require exchanges of information between the different computing units, at the risk of a loss of efficiency.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] A load-balancing algorithm always tries to answer a specific problem.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Among other things, the nature of the tasks, the algorithmic complexity, the hardware architecture on which the algorithms will run as well as required error tolerance, must be taken into account.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Therefore compromise must be found to best meet application-specific requirements.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of load balancing algorithms critically depends on the nature of the tasks.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the more information about the tasks is available at the time of decision making, the greater the potential for optimization.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Perfect knowledge of the execution time of each of the tasks allows to reach an optimal load distribution (see algorithm of prefix sum).
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Unfortunately, this is in fact an idealized case.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Knowing the exact execution time of each task is an extremely rare situation.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] For this reason, there are several techniques to get an idea of the different execution times.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] First of all, when tasks are relatively homogeneous size, it is possible to consider that each of them will require approximately the average execution time.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the execution time is considerably irregular, other techniques may be used.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] One technique is to add some metadata to each task.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Depending on the previous execution time for similar metadata, it is possible to make inferences for a future task based on statistics.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] In some cases, tasks depend on each other.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] These interdependencies can be illustrated by a directed acyclic graph.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Intuitively, some tasks cannot begin until others are completed.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Assuming that the required time for each of the tasks is known in advance, an optimal execution order must lead to the minimization of the total execution time.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] However, this is an NP-hard problem and therefore can be difficult to solve exactly.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] There are algorithms, like job scheduler, that calculate optimal task distributions using metaheuristic methods.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Another feature of the tasks critical for the design of a load balancing algorithm is their ability to be broken down into subtasks during execution.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The *tree-shaped computation* algorithm presented later takes great advantage of this specificity.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm is "static" when it does not take into account the state of the system for the distribution of tasks.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Thereby, the system state includes measures such as the load level (and sometimes even overload) of certain processors.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Instead, assumptions about the overall system are made beforehand, such as the arrival times and resource requirements of incoming tasks.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] In addition, the number of processors, their respective power and communication speeds are known.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, static load balancing aims to associate a known set of tasks with the available processors in order to minimize a certain performance function.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The key design choice is the performance function.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing techniques are commonly centralized around a router, or master, which distributes the loads and optimizes the performance function.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This minimization can take into account information related to the tasks to be distributed, and derive an expected execution time.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The advantage of static algorithms is that they are easy to set up and can efficient in the case of fairly regular tasks (such as processing HTTP requests from a website).
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] However, there is still some statistical variance in the assignment of tasks which can lead to the overloading of some computing units.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Unlike static load distribution algorithms, dynamic algorithms take into account the current load of each of the computing units (also called nodes) in the system.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] In this approach, tasks can be moved dynamically from an overloaded node to an underloaded node in order to receive faster processing.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] While these algorithms are much more complicated to design, they can improve performance, in particular, when the execution time varies greatly from one task to another.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing architecture can be more modular since it is not mandatory to have a specific node dedicated to the distribution of work.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] When tasks are uniquely assigned to a processor according to their state at a given moment, it is a unique assignment.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the tasks can be permanently redistributed according to the state of the system and its evolution, this is called dynamic assignment.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm that requires too much communication in order to reach its decisions runs the risk of slowing down the resolution of the overall problem.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Parallel computing infrastructures are often composed of units of different computing power, which should be taken into account for the load distribution.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] For example, lower-powered units may receive requests that require a smaller amount of computation, or, in the case of homogeneous or unknown request sizes, receive fewer requests than larger units.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] For shared-memory computers, managing write conflicts greatly slows down the speed of individual execution of each computing unit.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] However, they can work perfectly well in parallel.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Conversely, in the case of message exchange, each of the processors can work at full speed.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, when it comes to collective message exchange, all processors are forced to wait for the slowest processors to start the communication phase.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] In reality, few systems fall into exactly one of the categories.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] In general, the processors each have an internal memory to store the data needed for the next calculations and are organized in successive clusters.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Often, these processing elements are then coordinated through distributed memory and message passing.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the load balancing algorithm should be uniquely adapted to a parallel architecture.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Otherwise, there is a risk that the efficiency of parallel problem solving will be greatly reduced.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Adapting to the hardware structures seen above, there are two main categories of load balancing algorithms.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] On the one hand, the one where tasks are assigned by “master” and executed by “workers” who keep the master informed of the progress of their work, and the master can then take charge of assigning or reassigning the workload in case of the dynamic algorithm.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The literature refers to this as master-worker architecture.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, the control can be distributed between the different nodes.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The load balancing algorithm is then executed on each of them and the responsibility for assigning tasks (as well as re-assigning and splitting as appropriate) is shared.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The last category assumes a dynamic load balancing algorithm.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Since the design of each load balancing algorithm is unique, the previous distinction must be qualified.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Thus, it is also possible to have an intermediate strategy, with, for example, "master" nodes for each sub-cluster, which are themselves subject to a global "master".
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] There are also multi-level organizations, with an alternation between master-slave and distributed control strategies.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The latter strategies quickly become complex and are rarely encountered.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Designers prefer algorithms that are easier to control.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] In the context of algorithms that run over the very long term (servers, cloud...), the computer architecture evolves over time.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] However, it is preferable not to have to design a new algorithm each time.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] One parameter of a load balancing algorithm is therefore its ability to adapt to scalable hardware architecture.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This is called the scalability of the algorithm.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] An algorithm is called scalable for an input parameter when its performance remains relatively independent of the size of that parameter.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] When the algorithm is capable of adapting to a varying number of computing units, but the number of computing units must be fixed before execution, it is called moldable.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the algorithm is capable of dealing with a fluctuating amount of processors during its execution, the algorithm is said to be malleable.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancing algorithms are at least moldable.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Especially in large-scale computing clusters, it is not tolerable to execute a parallel algorithm that cannot withstand the failure of one single component.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, fault tolerant algorithms are being developed which can detect outages of processors and recover the computation.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] If the tasks are independent of each other, and if their respective execution time and the tasks can be subdivided, an optimal optimal algorithm is available under these assumptions.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] By dividing the tasks in such a way as to give the same amount of computation to each processor, all that remains to be done is to group the results together.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Using a prefix sum algorithm, this division can be calculated in logarithmic time with respect to the number of processors.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Most of the time, the execution time of a task is unknown and only rough approximations are available.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm may be efficient under these assumptions, but is less applicable when task durations are unknown.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Even if the execution time is not known in advance at all, static load distribution is always possible.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] In a round-robin algorithm, the first request is sent to the first server, then the next to the second, and so on down to the last.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Then it is started again, assigning the next request to the first server, and so on.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm can be weighted such that the most powerful units receive the largest number of requests and receive them first.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Randomized static load balancing is simply a matter of randomly assigning tasks to the different servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the number of tasks is known in advance, it is even more efficient to calculate a random permutation in advance.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This avoids communication costs for each assignment.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] There is no longer a need for a distribution master because every processor knows what task is assigned to it.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Even if the number of tasks is unknown, it is still possible to avoid communication with a pseudo-random assignment generation known to all processors.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The performance of this strategy (measured in total execution time for a given fixed set of tasks) decreases with the maximum size of the tasks.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Master-worker schemes are among the simplest dynamic load balancing algorithms.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] A master distributes the workload to all workers (also sometimes referred to as "slaves").
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Initially, all workers are idle and report this to the master.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The master answers worker requests and distributes the tasks to them.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] When he has no more tasks to give, he informs the workers so that they stop asking for tasks.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This scheme can distribute work evenly when assignment overhead is low.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Without taking into account the time needed for the assignment, the execution time would be comparable to the prefix sum seen above.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The problem with this algorithm is that it has difficulty adapting to a large number of processors because of the high amount of necessary communications.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This lack of scalability makes it quickly inoperable in very large servers or very large parallel computers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] However, the quality of the algorithm can be greatly improved by replacing the master with a task list that can be used by different processors.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Although this algorithm can be said to be slightly more difficult to implement, it can improve scalability, although still insufficient for very large computing centers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Another technique to overcome scalability problems when the time needed for task completion is unknown is work stealing.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The approach consists of assigning to each processor a certain number of tasks in a random or predefined manner, then allowing inactive processors to "steal" work from active or overloaded processors.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Several implementations of this concept exist, defined by a task division model and by the rules determining the exchange between processors.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] While this technique can be particularly effective, it is difficult to implement because it is necessary to ensure that communication does not become the primary occupation of the processors instead of solving the problem.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] In the case of atomic tasks, two main strategies can be distinguished, those where the processors with low load offer their computing capacity to those with the highest load, and those were the most loaded units wish to lighten the workload assigned to them.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] It has been shown that when the network is heavily loaded, it is more efficient for the least loaded units to offer their availability and when the network is lightly loaded, it is the overloaded processors that require support from the most inactive ones.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This rule of thumb limits the number of exchanged messages.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] In the case where one starts from a single large task that cannot be divided beyond an atomic level, a "Tree-Shaped computation" algorithm can be used, where the parent task is distributed in a work tree.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Initially, many processors have an empty task, except one that works sequentially on it.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Idle processors issue requests randomly to other processors (not necessarily active).
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] If the latter is able to subdivide the task it is working on, it does so by sending part of its work to the node making the request.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] It is then necessary to send a termination signal to the parent processor when the subtask is completed so that it, in turn, sends the message to its parent until it reaches the root of the tree.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] When the first processor, i.e. the root, has finished, a global termination message can be broadcast.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] In the end, it is necessary to assemble the results by going back up the tree.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of such an algorithm is close to the prefix sum when the job cutting and communication time is not too high compared to the work to be done.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] To avoid too high communication costs, it is possible to imagine a list of jobs on shared memory.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, a request is simply reading from a certain position on this shared memory at the request of the master processor.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] In addition to efficient problem solving through parallel computations, load balancing algorithms are widely used in HTTP request management where a site with a large audience must be able to handle a large number of requests per second.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] One of the most commonly used applications of load balancing is to provide a single Internet service from multiple servers, sometimes known as a server farm.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Commonly load-balanced systems include popular web sites, large Internet Relay Chat networks, high-bandwidth File Transfer Protocol (FTP) sites, Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) servers, Domain Name System (DNS) servers, and databases.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Round-robin DNS is an alternate method of load balancing that does not require a dedicated software or hardware node.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] In this technique, multiple IP addresses are associated with a single domain name; clients are given IP in a round-robin fashion.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] IP is assigned to clients with a short expiration so the client is more likely to use a different IP the next time they access the Internet service being requested.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Another more effective technique for load-balancing using DNS is to delegate www.example.org as a sub-domain whose zone is served by each of the same servers that are serving the website.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This technique works particularly well where individual servers are spread geographically on the Internet.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] However, the zone file for www.example.org on each server is different such that each server resolves its own IP Address as the A-record.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This way, when a server is down, its DNS will not respond and the web service does not receive any traffic.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] If the line to one server is congested, the unreliability of DNS ensures less HTTP traffic reaches that server.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Furthermore, the quickest DNS response to the resolver is nearly always the one from the network's closest server, ensuring geo-sensitive load-balancing .
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] A short TTL on the A-record helps to ensure traffic is quickly diverted when a server goes down.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Consideration must be given to the possibility that this technique may cause individual clients to switch between individual servers in mid-session.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Another approach to load balancing is to deliver a list of server IPs to the client, and then to have the client randomly select the IP from the list on each connection.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This essentially relies on all clients generating similar loads, and the law of large numbers to achieve a reasonably flat load distribution across servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] With this approach, the method of delivery of a list of IPs to the client can vary and may be implemented as a DNS list (delivered to all the clients without any round-robin), or via hardcoding it to the list.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] If a "smart client" is used, detecting that a randomly selected server is down and connecting randomly again, it also provides fault tolerance.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] For Internet services, a server-side load balancer is usually a software program that is listening on the port where external clients connect to access services.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer forwards requests to one of the "backend" servers, which usually replies to the load balancer.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This allows the load balancer to reply to the client without the client ever knowing about the internal separation of functions.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] It also prevents clients from contacting back-end servers directly, which may have security benefits by hiding the structure of the internal network and preventing attacks on the kernel's network stack or unrelated services running on other ports.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancers provide a mechanism for doing something special in the event that all backend servers are unavailable.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This might include forwarding to a backup load balancer or displaying a message regarding the outage.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] It is also important that the load balancer itself does not become a single point of failure.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Usually, load balancers are implemented in high-availability pairs which may also replicate session persistence data if required by the specific application.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Certain applications are programmed with immunity to this problem, by offsetting the load balancing point over differential sharing platforms beyond the defined network.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The sequential algorithms paired to these functions are defined by flexible parameters unique to the specific database.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Numerous scheduling algorithms, also called load-balancing methods, are used by load balancers to determine which back-end server to send a request to.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Simple algorithms include random choice, round robin, or least connections.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] An important issue when operating a load-balanced service is how to handle information that must be kept across the multiple requests in a user's session.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] If this information is stored locally on one backend server, then subsequent requests going to different backend servers would not be able to find it.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This might be cached information that can be recomputed, in which case load-balancing a request to a different backend server just introduces a performance issue.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Ideally, the cluster of servers behind the load balancer should not be session-aware, so that if a client connects to any backend server at any time the user experience is unaffected.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This is usually achieved with a shared database or an in-memory session database like Memcached.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] One basic solution to the session data issue is to send all requests in a user session consistently to the same backend server.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This is known as "persistence" or "stickiness".
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] A significant downside to this technique is its lack of automatic failover: if a backend server goes down, its per-session information becomes inaccessible, and any sessions depending on it are lost.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The same problem is usually relevant to central database servers; even if web servers are "stateless" and not "sticky", the central database is (see below).
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Assignment to a particular server might be based on a username, client IP address, or random.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Because of changes in the client's perceived address resulting from DHCP, network address translation, and web proxies this method may be unreliable.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Random assignments must be remembered by the load balancer, which creates a burden on storage.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] If the load balancer is replaced or fails, this information may be lost, and assignments may need to be deleted after a timeout period or during periods of high load to avoid exceeding the space available for the assignment table.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The random assignment method also requires that clients maintain some state, which can be a problem, for example when a web browser has disabled the storage of cookies.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Sophisticated load balancers use multiple persistence techniques to avoid some of the shortcomings of any one method.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Another solution is to keep the per-session data in a database.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This can reduce performance because it increases the load on the database: the database is best used to store information less transient than per-session data.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] To prevent a database from becoming a single point of failure, and to improve scalability, the database is often replicated across multiple machines, and load balancing is used to spread the query load across those replicas.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Microsoft's ASP.net State Server technology is an example of a session database.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] All servers in a web farm store their session data on State Server and any server in the farm can retrieve the data.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] When the client is a web browser, one approach is to store the per-session data in the browser itself.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] One way to achieve this is to use a browser cookie, suitably time-stamped and encrypted.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Storing session data on the client is generally the preferred solution: then the load balancer is free to pick any backend server to handle a request.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] However, this method of state-data handling may be unsuitable for some complex business logic scenarios, where the session state payload is large and recomputing it with every request on a server is not feasible.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] URL rewriting has major security issues because the end-user can easily alter the submitted URL and thus change session streams.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Yet another solution to storing persistent data is to associate a name with each block of data, and use a distributed hash table to pseudo-randomly assign that name to one of the available servers, and then store that block of data in the assigned server.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Hardware and software load balancers may have a variety of special features.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The fundamental feature of a load balancer is to be able to distribute incoming requests over a number of backend servers in the cluster according to a scheduling algorithm.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] A ratio can be manually assigned to cause some backend servers to get a greater share of the workload than others.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This is sometimes used as a simple way to account for some servers having more capacity than others, though it may not always work as desired.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] When the number of available servers drops below a certain number, or the load gets too high, standby servers can be brought online.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] request can become a major part of the demand on the Web Server's CPU; as the demand increases, users will see slower response times, as the TLS overhead is distributed among Web servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] To remove this demand on Web servers, a balancer can terminate TLS connections, passing HTTPS requests as HTTP requests to the Web servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] If the balancer itself is not overloaded, this does not noticeably degrade the performance perceived by end-users.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The downside of this approach is that all of the TLS processing is concentrated on a single device (the balancer) which can become a new bottleneck.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancer appliances include specialized hardware to process TLS.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Instead of upgrading the load balancer, which is quite expensive dedicated hardware, it may be cheaper to forgo TLS offload and add a few web servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Also, some server vendors such as Oracle/Sun now incorporate cryptographic acceleration hardware into their CPUs such as the T2000.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] F5 Networks incorporates a dedicated TLS acceleration hardware card in their local traffic manager (LTM) which is used for encrypting and decrypting TLS traffic.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] One clear benefit to TLS offloading in the balancer is that it enables it to do balancing or content switching based on data in the HTTPS request.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] attacks and generally offload work from the servers to a more efficient platform.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] compression available in all modern web browsers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The larger the response and the further away the client is, the more this feature can improve response times.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The trade-off is that this feature puts additional CPU demand on the load balancer and could be done by web servers instead.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Different vendors use different terms for this, but the idea is that normally each HTTP request from each client is a different TCP connection.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This feature utilises HTTP/1.1 to consolidate multiple HTTP requests from multiple clients into a single TCP socket to the back-end servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer can buffer responses from the server and spoon-feed the data out to slow clients, allowing the webserver to free a thread for other tasks faster than it would if it had to send the entire request to the client directly.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] An option for asymmetrical load distribution, where request and reply have different network paths.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The balancer polls servers for application layer health and removes failed servers from the pool.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The balancer stores static content so that some requests can be handled without contacting the servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can arbitrarily modify traffic on the way through.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can hide HTTP error pages, remove server identification headers from HTTP responses, and encrypt cookies so that end users cannot manipulate them.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] , the ability to give different priorities to different traffic.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancers can send requests to different servers based on the URL being requested, assuming the request is not encrypted (HTTP) or if it is encrypted (via HTTPS) that the HTTPS request is terminated (decrypted) at the load balancer.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Authenticate users against a variety of authentication sources before allowing them access to a website.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] At least one balancer allows the use of a scripting language to allow custom balancing methods, arbitrary traffic manipulations, and more.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Firewalls can prevent direct connections to backend servers, for network security reasons.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Intrusion prevention systems offer application layer security in addition to the network/transport layer offered by firewall security.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can be useful in applications with redundant communications links.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] For example, a company may have multiple Internet connections ensuring network access if one of the connections fails.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] A failover arrangement would mean that one link is designated for normal use, while the second link is used only if the primary link fails.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Using load balancing, both links can be in use all the time.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] A device or program monitors the availability of all links and selects the path for sending packets.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The use of multiple links simultaneously increases the available bandwidth.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) facilitates an Ethernet to have an arbitrary topology, and enables per flow pair-wise load splitting by way of Dijkstra's algorithm, without configuration and user intervention.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, whom in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The IEEE approved the IEEE 802.1aq standard in May 2012, also known as Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] SPB allows all links to be active through multiple equal-cost paths, provides faster convergence times to reduce downtime, and simplifies the use of load balancing in mesh network topologies (partially connected and/or fully connected) by allowing traffic to load share across all paths of a network.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] SPB is designed to reduce configuration errors and preserves the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at Layer 2.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Many telecommunications companies have multiple routes through their networks or to external networks.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] They use sophisticated load balancing to shift traffic from one path to another to avoid network congestion on any particular link, and sometimes to minimize the cost of transit across external networks or improve network reliability.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Another way of using load balancing is in network monitoring activities.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Load balancers can be used to split huge data flows into several sub-flows and use several network analyzers, each reading a part of the original data.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This can be used for monitoring fast networks like 10GbE or STM64, where complex processing of the data may not be possible at wire speed.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is widely used in data center networks to distribute traffic across many existing paths between any two servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] It allows more efficient use of network bandwidth and reduces provisioning costs.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] In general, load balancing in datacenter networks can be classified as either static or dynamic.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing distributes traffic by computing a hash of the source and destination addresses and port numbers of traffic flows and using it to determine how flows are assigned to one of the existing paths.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing assigns traffic flows to paths by monitoring bandwidth use on different paths.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic assignments can also be proactive or reactive.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] In the former case, the assignment is fixed once made, while in the latter the network logic keeps monitoring available paths and shifts flows across them as network utilization changes (with arrival of new flows or completion of existing ones).
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] A comprehensive overview of load balancing in datacenter networks has been made available.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is often used to implement failover—the continuation of service after the failure of one or more of its components.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] The components are monitored continually (e.g., web servers may be monitored by fetching known pages), and when one becomes unresponsive, the load balancer is informed and no longer sends traffic to it.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] When a component comes back online, the load balancer starts rerouting traffic to it.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] For this to work, there must be at least one component in excess of the service's capacity (N+1 redundancy).
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This can be much less expensive and more flexible than failover approaches where every single live component is paired with a single backup component that takes over in the event of a failure (dual modular redundancy).
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Some RAID systems can also utilize hot spare for a similar effect.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] This technique can increase fault tolerance by enabling quick substitutions for the most complicated, most failure-prone parts of a system.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] However, it can make the load balancer itself a single point of failure.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] To maintain the necessary high throughput and low latency, organizations commonly deploy load balancing tools capable of advanced TCP optimizations, connection pooling, and adaptive scheduling.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] Such features help distribute incoming data requests evenly across servers or nodes, prevent congestion, and ensure that compute resources remain efficiently utilized.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] When deployed in large-scale or high-performance AI environments, load balancers also mitigate bandwidth constraints and accommodate varying data governance requirements—particularly when sensitive training data cannot be sent to third-party cloud services.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] By routing data locally (on-premises) or across private clouds, load balancers allow AI workflows to avoid public-cloud bandwidth limits, reduce transit costs, and maintain compliance with regulatory standards.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/load-balancing-computing] As AI models expand in size (often measured by billions or even trillions of parameters), load balancing for data ingestion has grown in importance for maintaining the reliability, scalability, and cost efficiency of AI factories.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] In the field of computer networking and other packet-switched telecommunication networks, quality of service refers to traffic prioritization and resource reservation control mechanisms rather than the achieved service quality.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Quality of service is the ability to provide different priorities to different applications, users, or data flows, or to guarantee a certain level of performance to a data flow.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Quality of service is particularly important for the transport of traffic with special requirements, including voice over IP and other audio networking techniques, professional video over IP, card-based payments, and real-time computing.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] In the field of telephony, quality of service was defined by the ITU in 1994.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Quality of service comprises requirements on all the aspects of a connection, such as service response time, loss, signal-to-noise ratio, crosstalk, echo, interrupts, frequency response, loudness levels, and so on.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] A subset of telephony QoS is grade of service (GoS) requirements, which comprises aspects of a connection relating to capacity and coverage of a network, for example, guaranteed maximum blocking probability and outage probability.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] In the field of computer networking and other packet-switched telecommunication networks, teletraffic engineering refers to traffic prioritization and resource reservation control mechanisms rather than the achieved service quality.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] For example, a required bit rate, delay, delay variation, packet loss or bit error rates may be guaranteed.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Quality of service is important for real-time streaming multimedia applications such as voice over IP, multiplayer online games and IPTV, since these often require a fixed bit rate and are delay sensitive.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Quality of service is especially important in networks where the capacity is a limited resource, for example, in cellular data communication.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] A network or protocol that supports QoS may agree on a traffic contract with the application software and reserve capacity in the network nodes, for example during a session establishment phase.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] During the session, it may monitor the achieved level of performance, for example, the data rate and delay, and dynamically control scheduling priorities in the network nodes.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] It may release the reserved capacity during a tear down phase.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] A best-effort network or service does not support quality of service.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] An alternative to complex QoS control mechanisms is to provide high-quality communication over a best-effort network by over-provisioning the capacity so that it is sufficient for the expected peak traffic load.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] The resulting absence of network congestion reduces or eliminates the need for QoS mechanisms.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] QoS is sometimes used as a quality measure, with many alternative definitions, rather than referring to the ability to reserve resources.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Quality of service sometimes refers to the level of quality of service, i.e. the guaranteed service quality.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] High QoS is often confused with a high level of performance, for example high bit rate, low latency and low bit error rate.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] QoS is sometimes used in application layer services such as telephony and streaming video to describe a metric that reflects or predicts the subjectively experienced quality.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] In this context, QoS is the acceptable cumulative effect on subscriber satisfaction of all imperfections affecting the service.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Other terms with similar meaning are the quality of experience (QoE), mean opinion score (MOS), perceptual speech quality measure (PSQM) and perceptual evaluation of video quality (PEVQ).
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] A number of attempts for layer 2 technologies that add QoS tags to the data have gained popularity in the past.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Examples are Frame Relay, Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) and Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) (a technique between layer 2 and 3).
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Despite these network technologies remaining in use today, this kind of network lost attention after the advent of Ethernet networks.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Today, Ethernet is, by far, the most popular layer 2 technology.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Conventional Internet routers and network switches operate on a best-effort basis.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] This equipment is less expensive, less complex and faster and thus more popular than earlier, more complex technologies that provide QoS mechanisms.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Ethernet optionally uses 802.1p to signal the priority of a frame.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] There were four *type of service* bits and three *precedence* bits originally provided in each IP packet header, but they were not generally respected.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] These bits were later re-defined as Differentiated services code points (DSCP).
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] With the advent of IPTV and IP telephony, QoS mechanisms are increasingly available to the end user.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] In packet-switched networks, quality of service is affected by various factors, which can be divided into human and technical factors.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Human factors include: stability of service quality, availability of service, waiting times and user information.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Technical factors include: reliability, scalability, effectiveness, maintainability and network congestion.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Due to varying load from disparate users sharing the same network resources, the maximum throughput that can be provided to a certain data stream may be too low for real-time multimedia services.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] The network may fail to deliver (*drop*) some packets due to network congestion.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] The receiving application may ask for this information to be retransmitted, possibly resulting in congestive collapse or unacceptable delays in the overall transmission.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Sometimes packets are corrupted due to bit errors caused by noise and interference, especially in wireless communications and long copper wires.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] The receiver has to detect this, and, just as if the packet was dropped, may ask for this information to be retransmitted.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] It might take a long time for each packet to reach its destination because it gets held up in long queues, or it takes a less direct route to avoid congestion.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] In some cases, excessive latency can render an application such as VoIP or online gaming unusable.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Packets from the source will reach the destination with different delays.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] A packet's delay varies with its position in the queues of the routers along the path between source and destination, and this position can vary unpredictably.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Delay variation can be absorbed at the receiver, but in so doing increases the overall latency for the stream.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] When a collection of related packets is routed through a network, different packets may take different routes, each resulting in a different delay.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] The result is that the packets arrive in a different order than they were sent.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] This problem requires special additional protocols for rearranging out-of-order packets.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] The reordering process requires additional buffering at the receiver, and, as with packet delay variation, increases the overall latency for the stream.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] These types of service are called *inelastic*, meaning that they require a certain minimum bit rate and a certain maximum latency to function.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] By contrast, *elastic* applications can take advantage of however much or little bandwidth is available.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Bulk file transfer applications that rely on TCP are generally elastic.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Circuit-switched networks, especially those intended for voice transmission, such as ATM or GSM, have QoS in the core protocol; resources are reserved at each step on the network for the call as it is set up, and there is no need for additional procedures to achieve the required performance.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Shorter data units and built-in QoS were some of the unique selling points of ATM for applications such as video on demand.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] An alternative to complex QoS control mechanisms is to provide high-quality communication by generously over-provisioning a network so that capacity is based on peak traffic load estimates.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] This approach is simple for networks with predictable peak loads.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] This calculation may need to appreciate demanding applications that can compensate for variations in bandwidth and delay with large receive buffers, which is often possible, for example, in video streaming.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Over-provisioning can be of limited use in the face of transport protocols (such as TCP) that, over time, increase the amount of data placed on the network until all available bandwidth is consumed and packets are dropped.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Such greedy protocols tend to increase latency and packet loss for all users.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] The amount of over-provisioning in interior links required to replace QoS depends on the number of users and their traffic demands.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] This limits the usability of over-provisioning.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Newer, more bandwidth-intensive applications and the addition of more users result in the loss of over-provisioned networks.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] This then requires a physical update of the relevant network links, which is an expensive process.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Thus, over-provisioning cannot be blindly assumed on the Internet.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Commercial VoIP services are often competitive with traditional telephone service in terms of call quality, even without QoS mechanisms in use on the user's connection to their ISP and the VoIP provider's connection to a different ISP.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Under high load conditions, however, VoIP may degrade to cell-phone quality or worse.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] The mathematics of packet traffic indicates that the network requires just 60% more raw capacity under conservative assumptions.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Unlike single-owner networks, the Internet is a series of exchange points interconnecting private networks.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Hence the Internet's core is owned and managed by a number of different network service providers, not a single entity.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Its behavior is much more unpredictable.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] There are two principal approaches to QoS in modern packet-switched IP networks: a parameterized system based on an exchange of application requirements with the network, and a prioritized system where each packet identifies a desired service level to the network.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Early work used the integrated services (IntServ) philosophy of reserving network resources.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] In this model, applications used RSVP to request and reserve resources through a network.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] While IntServ mechanisms do work, it was realized that in a broadband network typical of a larger service provider, Core routers would be required to accept, maintain, and tear down thousands or possibly tens of thousands of reservations.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] It was believed that this approach would not scale with the growth of the Internet, and in any event was antithetical to the end-to-end principle, the notion of designing networks so that core routers do little more than simply switch packets at the highest possible rates.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Under DiffServ, packets are marked either by the traffic sources themselves or by the edge devices where the traffic enters the network.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] In response to these markings, routers and switches use various queuing strategies to tailor performance to requirements.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] At the IP layer, DSCP markings use the 6-bit DS field in the IP packet header.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] At the MAC layer, VLAN IEEE 802.1Q can be used to carry 3 bits of essentially the same information.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Routers and switches supporting DiffServ configure their network scheduler to use multiple queues for packets awaiting transmission from bandwidth-constrained (e.g., wide area) interfaces.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Router vendors provide different capabilities for configuring this behavior, including the number of queues supported, the relative priorities of queues, and the bandwidth reserved for each queue.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] In practice, when a packet must be forwarded from an interface with queuing, packets requiring low jitter (e.g., VoIP or videoconferencing) are given priority over packets in other queues.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Typically, some bandwidth is allocated by default to network control packets (such as Internet Control Message Protocol and routing protocols), while best-effort traffic might simply be given whatever bandwidth is left over.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] At the medium access control (MAC) layer, VLAN IEEE 802.1Q and IEEE 802.1p can be used to distinguish between Ethernet frames and classify them.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Queueing theory models have been developed on performance analysis and QoS for MAC layer protocols.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Cisco IOS NetFlow and the Cisco Class Based QoS (CBQoS) Management Information Base (MIB) are marketed by Cisco Systems.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] One compelling example of the need for QoS on the Internet relates to congestive collapse.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] The Internet relies on congestion avoidance protocols, primarily as built into Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), to reduce traffic under conditions that would otherwise lead to congestive collapse.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] QoS applications, such as VoIP and IPTV, require largely constant bitrates and low latency, therefore they cannot use TCP and cannot otherwise reduce their traffic rate to help prevent congestion.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Service-level agreements limit traffic that can be offered to the Internet and thereby enforce traffic shaping that can prevent it from becoming overloaded, and are hence an indispensable part of the Internet's ability to handle a mix of real-time and non-real-time traffic without collapse.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Several QoS mechanisms and schemes exist for IP networking.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] QoS capabilities are available in the following network technologies.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] End-to-end quality of service can require a method of coordinating resource allocation between one autonomous system and another.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) defined the Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) for bandwidth reservation as a proposed standard in 1997.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] RSVP is an end-to-end bandwidth reservation and admission control protocol.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] RSVP was not widely adopted due to scalability limitations.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] The more scalable traffic engineering version, RSVP-TE, is used in many networks to establish traffic-engineered Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) label-switched paths.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] The IETF also defined Next Steps in Signaling (NSIS) with QoS signalling as a target.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] NSIS is a development and simplification of RSVP.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Research consortia such as "end-to-end quality of service support over heterogeneous networks" (EuQoS, from 2004 through 2007) and fora such as the IPsphere Forum developed more mechanisms for handshaking QoS invocation from one domain to the next.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] IPsphere defined the Service Structuring Stratum (SSS) signaling bus in order to establish, invoke and (attempt to) assure network services.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] EuQoS conducted experiments to integrate Session Initiation Protocol, Next Steps in Signaling and IPsphere's SSS with an estimated cost of about 15.6 million Euro and published a book.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] A research project Multi Service Access Everywhere (MUSE) defined another QoS concept in a first phase from January 2004 through February 2006, and a second phase from January 2006 through 2007.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Another research project named PlaNetS was proposed for European funding circa 2005.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] A broader European project called "Architecture and design for the future Internet" known as 4WARD had a budget estimated at 23.4 million Euro and was funded from January 2008 through June 2010.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] It included a "Quality of Service Theme" and published a book.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Another European project, called WIDENS (Wireless Deployable Network System), proposed a bandwidth reservation approach for mobile wireless multirate adhoc networks.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Strong cryptography network protocols such as Secure Sockets Layer, I2P, and virtual private networks obscure the data transferred using them.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] As all electronic commerce on the Internet requires the use of such strong cryptography protocols, unilaterally downgrading the performance of encrypted traffic creates an unacceptable hazard for customers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Yet, encrypted traffic is otherwise unable to undergo deep packet inspection for QoS.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Protocols like ICA and RDP may encapsulate other traffic (e.g. printing, video streaming) with varying requirements that can make optimization difficult.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] The Internet2 project found, in 2001, that the QoS protocols were probably not deployable inside its Abilene Network with equipment available at that time.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] The group predicted that "logistical, financial, and organizational barriers will block the way toward any bandwidth guarantees" by protocol modifications aimed at QoS.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] They believed that the economics would encourage network providers to deliberately erode the quality of best effort traffic as a way to push customers to higher-priced QoS services.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Instead, they proposed over-provisioning of capacity as more cost-effective at the time.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] The Abilene network study was the basis for the testimony of Gary Bachula to the US Senate Commerce Committee's hearing on Network Neutrality in early 2006.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] He expressed the opinion that adding more bandwidth was more effective than any of the various schemes for accomplishing QoS they examined.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Bachula's testimony has been cited by proponents of a law banning quality of service as proof that no legitimate purpose is served by such an offering.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] This argument is dependent on the assumption that over-provisioning isn't a form of QoS and that it is always possible.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Cost and other factors affect the ability of carriers to build and maintain permanently over-provisioned networks.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Mobile cellular service providers may offer mobile QoS to customers just as the wired public switched telephone network service providers and Internet service providers may offer QoS.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] QoS mechanisms are always provided for circuit switched services, and are essential for inelastic services, for example streaming multimedia.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Mobility adds complications to QoS mechanisms.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] A phone call or other session may be interrupted after a handover if the new base station is overloaded.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Unpredictable handovers make it impossible to give an absolute QoS guarantee during the session initiation phase.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Quality of service in the field of telephony was first defined in 1994 in ITU-T Recommendation E.800.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] This definition is very broad, listing 6 primary components: Support, Operability, Accessibility, Retainability, Integrity and Security.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] In 1998 the ITU published a document discussing QoS in the field of data networking.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] X.641 offers a means of developing or enhancing standards related to QoS and provides concepts and terminology that should assist in maintaining the consistency of related standards.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] Some QoS-related IETF Request for Comments (RFC)s are *Baker, Fred; Black, David L.; Nichols, Kathleen; Blake, Steven L.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] (December 1998), *Definition of the Differentiated services Field (DS Field) in the IPv4 and IPv6 Headers*, doi:10.17487/RFC2474, RFC 2474*, and *Braden, Robert T.; Zhang, Lixia; Berson, Steven; Herzog, Shai; Jamin, Sugih (September 1997), Braden, R.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] (ed.), *Resource ReSerVation Protocol (RSVP)*, doi:10.17487/RFC2205, RFC 2205*; both these are discussed above.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] The IETF has also published two RFCs giving background on QoS: *Huston, Geoff (November 2000), *Next Steps for the IP QoS Architecture*, doi:10.17487/RFC2990, RFC 2990*, and *Floyd, S.; Kempf, J.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] (ed.), *IAB Concerns Regarding Congestion Control for Voice Traffic in the Internet*, doi:10.17487/RFC3714, RFC 3714*.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/quality-of-service] The document tries to identify applications commonly run over an IP network, groups them into traffic classes, studies the treatment required by these classes from the network, and suggests which of the QoS mechanisms commonly available in routers can be used to implement those treatments.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] In computer networks, a **reverse proxy** or surrogate server is a proxy server that appears to any client to be an ordinary web server, but in reality merely acts as an intermediary that forwards the client's requests to one or more ordinary web servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies help increase scalability, performance, resilience, and security, but they also carry a number of risks.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] Companies that run web servers often set up reverse proxies to facilitate the communication between an Internet user's browser and the web servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] An important advantage of doing so is that the web servers can be hidden behind a firewall on a company-internal network, and only the reverse proxy needs to be directly exposed to the Internet.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxy servers are implemented in popular open-source web servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] Dedicated reverse proxy servers are used by some of the biggest websites on the Internet.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is capable of tracking IP addresses of requests that are relayed through it as well as reading and/or modifying any non-encrypted traffic.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] However, this implies that anyone who has compromised the server could do so as well.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies differ from forward proxies, which are used when the client is restricted to a private, internal network and asks a forward proxy to retrieve resources from the public Internet.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] Large websites and content delivery networks use reverse proxies, together with other techniques, to balance the load between internal servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can keep a cache of static content, which further reduces the load on these internal servers and the internal network.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] It is also common for reverse proxies to add features such as compression or TLS encryption to the communication channel between the client and the reverse proxy.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can inspect HTTP headers, which, for example, allows them to present a single IP address to the Internet while relaying requests to different internal servers based on the URL of the HTTP request.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can hide the existence and characteristics of origin servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] This can make it more difficult to determine the actual location of the origin server / website and, for instance, more challenging to initiate legal action such as takedowns or block access to the website, as the IP address of the website may not be immediately apparent.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] Additionally, the reverse proxy may be located in a different jurisdiction with different legal requirements, further complicating the takedown process.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] Application firewall features can protect against common web-based attacks, like a denial-of-service attack (DoS) or distributed denial-of-service attacks (DDoS).
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] Without a reverse proxy, removing malware or initiating takedowns (while simultaneously dealing with the attack) on one's own site, for example, can be difficult.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] In the case of secure websites, a web server may not perform TLS encryption itself, but instead offload the task to a reverse proxy that may be equipped with TLS acceleration hardware.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can distribute the load from incoming requests to several servers, with each server supporting its own application area.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] In the case of reverse proxying web servers, the reverse proxy may have to rewrite the URL in each incoming request in order to match the relevant internal location of the requested resource.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can reduce load on its origin servers by caching static content and dynamic content, known as web acceleration.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] Proxy caches of this sort can often satisfy a considerable number of website requests, greatly reducing the load on the origin server(s).
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can optimize content by compressing it in order to speed up loading times.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] In a technique named "spoon-feeding", a dynamically generated page can be produced in its entirety and served to the reverse proxy, which can feed the page to the client as the connection allows.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] The program that generates the page need not remain open, thus releasing server resources during the possibly extended time the client requires to complete the transfer.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can operate wherever multiple web-servers must be accessible via a single public IP address.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] The web servers listen on different ports in the same machine, with the same local IP address or, possibly, on different machines with different local IP addresses.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] The reverse proxy analyzes each incoming request and delivers it to the right server within the local area network.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can perform A/B testing and multivariate testing without requiring application code to handle the logic of which version is served to a client.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can add access authentication to a web server that does not have any authentication.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] When the transit traffic is encrypted and the reverse proxy needs to filter/cache/compress or otherwise modify or improve the traffic, the proxy first must decrypt and re-encrypt communications.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] This requires the proxy to possess the TLS certificate and its corresponding private key, extending the number of systems that can have access to non-encrypted data and making it a more valuable target for attackers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] The vast majority of external data breaches happen either when hackers succeed in abusing an existing reverse proxy that was intentionally deployed by an organization, or when hackers succeed in converting an existing Internet-facing server into a reverse proxy server.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] Compromised or converted systems allow external attackers to specify where they want their attacks proxied to, enabling their access to internal networks and systems.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] Applications that were developed for the internal use of a company are not typically hardened to public standards and are not necessarily designed to withstand all hacking attempts.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] When an organization allows external access to such internal applications via a reverse proxy, they might unintentionally increase their own attack surface and invite hackers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] If a reverse proxy is not configured to filter attacks or it does not receive daily updates to keep its attack signature database up to date, a zero-day vulnerability can pass through unfiltered, enabling attackers to gain control of the system(s) that are behind the reverse proxy server.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] Giving the reverse proxy of a third party access to private keys (for caching or optimizing content) places the entire triad of confidentiality, integrity and availability in the hands of the third party who operates the proxy.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is a single point of failure for the back-end services it fronts: an outage caused by misconfiguration, a denial-of-service attack, or a software fault can make every fronted service unreachable to outside clients, even when the back-end services themselves remain healthy.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/reverse-proxy] For example, a 2020 outage at Cloudflare briefly took down major sites and services that relied on its reverse-proxy edge, including Discord.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] In its simplest implementation, round-robin DNS works by responding to DNS requests not only with a single potential IP address, but with a list of potential IP addresses corresponding to several servers that host identical services.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] The order in which IP addresses from the list are returned is the basis for the term *round robin*.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] With each DNS response, the IP address sequence in the list is permuted.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] Traditionally, IP clients initially attempt connections with the first address returned from a DNS query, so that on different connection attempts, clients would receive service from different providers, thus distributing the overall load among servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] Some resolvers attempt to re-order the list to give priority to numerically "closer" networks.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] This behaviour was standardized in RFC 3484 during the definition of IPv6.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] When applied to IPv4, a bug in Windows Vista caused issues and defeated round-robin load-balancing.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] Some desktop clients do try alternate addresses after a connection timeout of up to 30 seconds.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] Round-robin DNS is often used to load balance requests among a number of web servers.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] For example, a company has one domain name and three identical copies of the same web site residing on three servers with three IP addresses.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] The DNS server will be set up so that domain name has multiple A records, one for each IP address.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] When one user accesses the home page it will be sent to the first IP address.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] The second user who accesses the home page will be sent to the next IP address, and the third user will be sent to the third IP address.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] In each case, once the IP address is given out, it goes to the end of the list.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] The fourth user, therefore, will be sent to the first IP address, and so forth.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] A round-robin DNS name is, on rare occasions, referred to as a "rotor" due to the rotation among alternative A records.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] Although easy to implement, round-robin DNS has a number of drawbacks, such as those arising from record caching in the DNS hierarchy itself, as well as client-side address caching and reuse, the combination of which can be difficult to manage.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] Round-robin DNS should not solely be relied upon for service availability.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] If a service at one of the addresses in the list fails, the DNS will continue to hand out that address and clients will still attempt to reach the inoperable service.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] Round-robin DNS may not be the best choice for load balancing on its own, since it merely alternates the order of the address records each time a name server is queried.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] Because it does not take transaction time, server load, and network congestion into consideration, it works best for services with a large number of uniformly distributed connections to servers of equivalent capacity.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] Otherwise, it just does load distribution.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] Methods exist to overcome such limitations.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] For example, modified DNS servers (such as lbnamed) can routinely poll mirrored servers for availability and load factor.
[src:load-balancing-l4-l7/round-robin-dns] If a server does not reply as required, the server can be temporarily removed from the DNS pool, until it reports that it is once again operating within specs.
